title.narrative: INCREASED QUALITY OF AND ACCESS TO Early Child Development (ECD)

description.narrative: Increased quality of and access to Early Child Development (ECD) services and awareness of parents on positive, gender sensitive Early Child Development (ECD) and care practices, including on adequate nutrition and timely immunization, especially for Roma and families with children with developmental difficulties and disabilities., which contributes to Cross-Sectoral Early Childhood Development, Early Childhood Development, Early Childhood Development (Covid), Health Systems Strengthening, Immunization, Infant And Young Child Feeding, Maternal And Newborn Health, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Violence, Exploitation And Abuse. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Increased percentage of young children, particularly Roma and CWD, benefitting from equitable, gender- sensitive, quality health and other Early Child Development (ECD) services and supportive parental practices

title.narrative: Increased quality of and access to ECD services and awareness of parents on positive, gender sensitive ECD and care practices,including on adequate nutrition and timely immunization, especially for Roma and families with children with developmentaldifficulties and disabilities.

description.narrative: Growing commitment to ECD at the national and local levels and increased professional and institutional capacities for supporting families of young children across sectors have been achieved over recent years. This has set the foundation for modelling cross-sectoral ECD and ECI services and establishing an enabling environment for further scale-up across the country. The COVID-19 response is capitalizing on evidence-based innovative solutions for the most vulnerable parents and young children and high-quality sustainable learning opportunities for professionals. Increasing the shift to family-centred, strength-based approaches in service provision and communication was critical to address the challenges associated with the COVID-19 pandemic. | Status:Met | As-of Date:18/12/2020
